Namaste,

In tradition, all rituals are avoided during=
 eclipse. Temples also close during 
the eclipse. However, answer to your q=
uestion is slightly nuanced.

Individualized consciousness is a microcosm, =
while the external universe is the 
macrocosm. They correspond to each othe=
r. The external Sun and Moon correspond 
to the individual soul and mind in=
 the microcosm. They are the eyes of the 
individualized consciousness, thr=
ough which various objects in the field of 
duality are "seen". When they a=
re closed, one is in samadhi and does not see the 
objects in the field of =
duality.

When Sun or Moon are eclipsed externally and do not shine, the in=
dividual soul 
or mind are weak and do not shine in the microcosm. Such tim=
es are conducive to 
activities that need the individual soul and mind to b=
e passive and silent, and 
unconducive to activites that need them to be ac=
tive and alert.

If one is doing rituals - japam or homam or abhishekam or =
any ritual - for 
material purposes, then individual consciousness needs to=
 keep its eyes open to 
the field of duality, seek some objects and reject =
some objects etc. So the eyes 
need to be wide open. Just as shooting an ar=
row (or a gun) at a target when 
there is a fly in the eye and you cannot k=
eep the eye open is a bad idea, times 
when Sun or Moon are eclipsed are un=
conducive to doing such sadhana aimed at 
material results.

If the goal of=
 one's sadhana is spiritual progress and self-realization, then 
one is aim=
ing to close the eyes of individualized consciousness and stop seeing 
the =
objects in the field of duality. Then, eclipse time is very auspicious. 
Th=
us, japam or homam or other rituals conducted at the time of an eclipse are=
 
very auspicious and can even put a nearly ready sadhaka in samadhi. Pract=
ice any 
ritual you want to practice (e.g. homam to your ishta) and then cl=
ose your eyes, 
keep the back straight, stop all physical movement and medi=
tate on your ishta.

Best regards,
Narasimha
